Extrication, immobilization and radiologic investigation of patients with cervical spine injuries. Most cervical spine injuries are due to motor vehicle accidents. Proper extrication of the victims is vital the ideal device should be easily assembled and applied, should facilitate removal of victims from automobile seats without changing the body's position, must not hinder airway access or the performance of cardiopulmonary resuscitation, must accommodate all types of patients, including children and obese or pregnant patients, and must completely immobilize the patient, especially if hyperextension is suspected. Current methods of immobilization, such as the use of a soft collar and sandbags, allow neck extension